f Boston, as if it reflects the full history and experience of Catholicism across the United States.The Making of American Catholicism argues that regional and transnational relationships have been central to the development of American Catholicism. The American Catholic experience has diverged significantly among regions; if we do not examine how it has taken shape in local cultures, we miss a lot. Exploring the history of Catholic cultures in New Orleans, Iowa, Wisconsin, Los Angeles, and New York City, the volume assesses the role of region in American Catholic history, carefully exploring the development of American Catholic cultures across the continental United States.Drawing on extensive archival research, The Making of American Catholicism argues that American Catholicism developed as transnational Catholics creatively adapted their devotional and ideological practices in particular American regional contexts. They emphasized notions of republicanism, individualistic capitalism, race, ethnicity, and gender, resulting in a unique form of Catholicism that dominates the United States today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Catholic.2bisacsh  aAfrican American Catholics.  aAmerican conservatism.  aAmerican nationalism.  aAmericanism.  aCatholicism and U.S. electoral politics.  aCatholicism in the American West.  aCatholicism in the Pacific Northwest.  aCatholics on the U.S.Supreme Court.  aCzech Catholics.  aEuropean immigrant Catholics.  aGerman Catholics.  aHispano-descended Catholics.  aIrish Catholics.  aIrish-American identity.  aLatinx Catholics.  aLos Angeles.  aLower Midwest.  aMarian Revival.  aMexican Catholics.  aMidwestern Catholicism.  aNew Orleans Catholicism.  aRegional Catholic cultures.  aSouthern California.  aUpper Midwester